in a nutshell, we see an often in/egress spikes of network degradation. that result to an almost complete cut-off of the network throughput. But only to specific domains. eg x10 delay in writing or reading to R2, or even timeouts to the subtensor nodes.

in my experience this happens for either of two reasons; the network has changed, resulting to a spontaneous bad IP routing, or the service is stalled for too long, resulting a network timeout from the other side (missed heartbeat) - this could happen either due to long garbage collections, or we hammer the I/O for too long so nothing else happens.

from my side, there're many levels of improvements I can consider. First of all i don't have a OS-level to monitor what has actually happen, right now we have app-level telemetry, we need OS so I can see whether we hamer I/O or the Apps are going stalled. Secondly, we can delegate the writing to R2 via mounted disks (via s3fs of rclone) that would be more reliable to sync the new files to R2, without causing the App to halt. And last one (more invasive change) is to see and change the code to be more friendlier in paralleling the I/O ops.

these are my thoughts.
